	<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Image Resizing</h2>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>What happens to image quality when I resize?</h3>
		<p>When downsizing (making images smaller), quality is generally preserved well using high-quality resampling algorithms. When upsizing (making images larger), some quality loss or pixelation may occur since you're adding pixels that don't exist in the original. For best results, always resize down from a high-resolution source image.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>What does "maintain aspect ratio" mean?</h3>
		<p>Aspect ratio is the proportional relationship between width and height. When enabled, changing one dimension automatically adjusts the other to keep the image from appearing stretched or squished. Disable it if you need exact custom dimensions and don't mind distortion.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>Can I resize images in batch?</h3>
		<p>Currently, this tool processes one image at a time for optimal performance and quality control. Simply resize each image individually - the process is very fast.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>What's the difference between resizing and compressing?</h3>
		<p>Resizing changes the pixel dimensions (width x height) of an image. Compression reduces file size by optimizing how the image data is stored. For maximum file size reduction, resize your image first, then use our <a href="../image-compressor/">Image Compressor</a>.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>Can I change the format while resizing?</h3>
		<p>Yes! Use the "Output Format" dropdown to convert your image to PNG, JPG, or WEBP while resizing. This is convenient for preparing images in the exact format and size you need.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>Is my image uploaded to your server?</h3>
		<p>No! This image resizer works entirely in your web browser using HTML5 Canvas technology. Your images are processed locally on your device and never uploaded anywhere. It's completely private and secure.</p>
	</div>
